A, B and D have two nominations, C only has one. So C is the least likely to be the traitor.

A, B and D each each been accused by two people. Very suspicious! 

Looking more closely, A accuses B. That is the only person they accuse.

B, C and D accuse two people each.

Let's say that each person can give out one accusation point, worth a score of 1.

If a person accuses just one other, they gives all of their accusation score to that person.

If they accuses two people, each person receives half an accusation point.

So A has given their entire accusation point to B, which is a more powerful accusation.

## What has this got to do with the internet?

If we squint our eyes, this simplified game of The Traitors is a little bit like the OG recommendation algorithm, Google's PageRank.

PageRank was developed by Google co-founders Larry Page and Sergey Brin. It was a groundbreaking idea that revolutionized how search engines should decide which results to show.

Lets say someone Google's the word 'frog'. We can check the entire internet and make a list of every website that contains the word 'frog'. That will probably be hundreds of thousands of websites.

We can't show all of the websites to the reader all at once, that would be overwhelming and their screen probably isn't big enough for a hundred thousands links.

It's probably better if we just show them ten results. But how do we pick that top ten? And which website should be number one?

Perhaps we could pick only websites that have the word 'frog' in the title? Or the websites that repeat the word 'frog' the most times? Or only websites that contain big pictures of frogs?

The PageRank algorithm does something different. It ranks each page based on the number and 'quality' of links from other website pointing to it. 

Essentially, each link is treated as a 'vote'. The site with the most votes wins.

Which is a little bit like our game of The Traitors, if we assume that the players are websites and instead of accusations, they are linking to each other. Which is much more wholesome.

## Quality links

The algorithm assumes that the more important a website is, the more likely it is to receive links from other websites.

But there is a problem with assuming that the page with the most incoming links is automatically the most important.

It's possible to game the system. A nasty person could simply launch hundreds of pointless websites, all linking to their main site just to make that site appear to be more important.

Let's say than B now also links to A.

