A now surpasses D in rank because it has a new recommendation.

However, more interestingly, A now has three incoming links, more than any other site, and yet site B is still ranked higher.

Site A only endorses one other site, site B. So it gives all of it's importance point to B.

Site B links to three sites, so it can only give a third of an importance point to Site A.

It's not just about the number of links, it's about the quality of those links. I other words, a page is more 'important', the more it is linked to by 'important' pages.

If a big, respected site like the BBC or the New York Times links to you, that will mean much more to your PageRank score than a link from my personal blog about ginger cats.

## How does PageRank decide who is best

PageRank uses a technique called the a __Random Surfer__. This is more than just an erratic water sports enthusiast. The Random Surfer represents an average internet user randomly clicking links on the web. 

